&ldquo;How do you do it?&rdquo; she asked me, &ldquo;How do you live alone and survive without falling into that lonesome pit of solitary depression?&rdquo;

That she was asking me was interesting enough I suppose. I&rsquo;m easily thirty years her junior and her life experience usually lent itself to me ask her for advice. But this incidence was unique in our encounters. Unique and somewhat disheartening.

I had fallen prey to another&rsquo;s mid-life crisis and as such was living in a small house with my two children doing the everyday things that a parent does, but I did do it alone. I had no partner to speak to in the depths of the night. I had to stay healthy when everyone else was ill. I was the only person who paid bills or called the plumber. I did things alone.

She, my neighbour, was a recent widow after being married longer than I had been alive and today was the day I had come over to offer her some of my surplus dinner. (I had made too much on purpose so that I could come and offer her the &lsquo;extra tattie&rsquo; from the pot.)

So over an obligatory cup of tea she asked me this heart felt question that changed the dynamic between the two of us.

I sipped my tea and then formed an answer. &ldquo;What you need to do is remember you lived alone before him. Remember your life before it was lived as part of a team. If you had the strength to do it before, you definitely have the strength to do it now.&rdquo;

I reached out and grabbed her hands. &ldquo; There were time when he was by your side and you were alone then too. Take strength in the fact that you survived loneliness living with someone. That is the worst kind, that is the kind the eats your soul up.&rdquo;

&ldquo;I am lucky I guess, that I was left alone so young, at a time where I have to live for the kids before myself. But that is hard too, because I didn&rsquo;t get to feel alone. But you have the joy of it, the room to stretch and breathe and feel alone or no feel alone as your choice.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Oh there are the terrible things to it as well, now there is no one to blame if the door isn&rsquo;t locked at night before bed. Now I am always the first one in the shower on a cold November morning, and a hot water bottle doesn&rsquo;t have arms to hug you back. But these things are bearable.&rdquo;

I stopped then, I stopped to drink my tea a little and I stopped so that I wouldn&rsquo;t preach. I&rsquo;ve sat in her seat before and I know sometimes that when you sit in that new lonely place you want answers but hearing them is something all together different.
